What did you think SNK was going to be like when you first got into it? Or at least before the timeskip.
>thought it'd be a sentimental and heartfelt horror-action manga where every character developed into someone meaningful to the story
>thought it'd either end with or climax with the realization that humans exist outside the walls, and that these humans may or may not be actively hostile or manipulating the walled folks
>really enjoyed Armin and had high hopes he'd continue to grow into a warm, "ideal husband" type of character who still had his realistic flaws
>thought all the odd parallels between Historia and Armin would lead to some big revelation about him being a royal or something
>always knew Eren would probably become the enemy, or at least betray the rest of the cast, but thought it wouldn't go at all the way it did, rather that he'd be growing closer and closer to everyone until suddenly he gets possessed or the real big bad controls him
>hoped it'd be a story about found family and all the loose ends would be tied up
So many fucking loose ends and foreshadowings that went literally nowhere. It blows my mind how botched this series was. I can empathize that it's Isayama's first manga (aside from a one shot), but fuck dude, it makes me want to rewrite the entire story from scratch to prove a point. (I'm not saying I'd write it how I described my expectations listed above, but rather I'd fix all the dead end bullshit and the absolute cringefest that was the final 10-20 chapters or so.)

com:
Boruto is a gateway anime of the best kind. It's a great series, with a story and characterization that is very well done in most aspects, and which bolsters its strengths with great character development and a dark, complicated plot. Your average anon, hopefully, is intelligent enough to see this as the masterpiece it is, and may enjoy it, hate it or be indifferent to it, but all the while recognizing that the series itself, regardless of their opinion, is very well thought out and deserves recognition and respect.

These very aspects that make the anime so deep and mature make it a discussion ground for scholarly gentlemen who engage in every kind of both online and in the real world. The hard-working characters who continue to stand against all odds, the realistic jutsus and well-designed clothes, the whole and everything about the complex Boruto world provides fuel for much thought, and the deep character backgrounds, their dark past and emphasis on revenge, and overall greatness of the series make it fit just right with the refined taste of your average intellectual and his sense of disappointment towards the world’s dull, un-thought provoking choices in entertainment. Exactly the kind of material that brings the intelligent and well-educated together over critical discussion.

Boruto is basically THE series to attract the highest-tier fanbase known to /a/, which is why, regardless of individual opinions, it is the responsibility of every anon to support the existence of threads discussing the subject, and make sure to give a friendly bump to all Boruto threads to make sure /a/’s elite continue to show their faces here.

com: How prevalent is it? Anime and manga, two extremely commercial industries, whose primary aim is to sell manga, and secondary aim is to sell licensed merchandise, are of course up to the gills in fanservice. Everything from character designs, storyline, character interactions are frequently predicated on giving the people what they want. Magazines frequently poll readers on what they like, editors frequently instruct mangaka to insert more crowd pleasing elements in their work, anime often casts talent based on their popularity and typecasting. So how common is it for anime and manga to forgo fanservice to tell stories that are not so commercially calculated or even indifferent to audience expectations?
